Plotting Roman Roads (update)

by jaro

update: 14 September 2021

Roman roads network

This post concerns representation of ancient Roman roads with data from the article:

Fousek J, Kaše V, Mertel A, Výtvarová E, Chalupa A (2018) Spatial constraints on the diffusion of religious innovations: The case of early Christianity in the Roman Empire. PLoS ONE 13(12): e0208744. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0208744

Preliminaries

Load "multigraph" package and check its version. 
# load package and check version
library("multigraph")
packageVersion("multigraph")
[1] '0.96'

Dataset

The dataset consists on three files of the Roman Empire transport network between ancient cities:

  • s007 edgelist with cities travel costs
  • s006 city or settlement labels and their coordinates
  • s008 city or population estimates (among others)

Edgelist

Retrieve file s007.txt from GH repo with the “Edge list of the travel network” (https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0208744.s007).

# Edge list of the travel network
s007 <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/sdam-au/R_code/master/data/s007.txt")

Look at some entries:

head(s007)
   from    to      cost
1 50176 50250 1.1616039
2 50176 50183 1.5454368
3 50176 50031 3.6945114
4 50177 50173 0.9312658
5 50177 50109 0.9578813
6 50178 50304 0.8077696

Object s007 then is a data frame with three columns; the two first columns record edges from and to ancient Roman cities coded with an ID. The third column has a weight of the travel cost (from-to..?) according to the ORBIS model where the minimum weight is:

min(s007[,,3])
[1] 0.07349514

Use function read.srt() from package "multiplex" to convert the edge list in s007 data frame into a matrix representing this network. In this case, the weights are the cells of the matrix.

# 's007' is a comma-separated table
net <- multiplex::read.srt(s007, header=TRUE, sep=",")

We look at the number of nodes in this network

dim(net)
[1] 648 648

and also at some of the entries in the net matrix for entity 50019.

net[18,1:6]
    50001     50002     50003     50004     50005     50006 
0.0000000 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.7754201

Graph representation

Since some travel cost weights are below 1, we need to make sure these entries also appear in the graph by scaling the matrix.

# force directed layout 
multigraph(net*100, directed=FALSE, layout="force", seed=1, pos=0)

Graph with Roman roads

City names

The network labels or the ancient Roman cities names are a file with coordinates (https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0208744.s006)

# List of nodes of the travel network.
s006 <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/sdam-au/R_code/master/data/s006.txt")

Look at some entries:

head(s006)
  objectid           label XCOORD YCOORD
1    50002   Ad fl. Tigrim 37.325 42.196
2    50209 Iulia Concordia 45.757 12.844
3    50327            Roma 41.892 12.486
4    50319      Praetorium   31.5   15.5
5    50294        Patavium  45.41 11.877
6    50322         Puteoli 40.824 14.122

Object lbs is a vector with city names found in s006 according to net, which is lexicographically ordered.

# second column in 's006' has the names
lbs <- as.vector(s006[match(as.numeric(dimnames(net)[[1]]), s006$objectid), 2])
# force directed layout with customized labels
multigraph(net*100, directed=FALSE, layout="force", seed=1, pos=0, lbs=lbs)

Graph with Roman cities and roads 

# force directed layout with customized labels
scp <- list(pos=0, ecol=8, col=8, fsize=5)
multigraph(net*100, directed=FALSE, layout="force", seed=1, scope=scp, lbs=lbs, fcol="#660066")

Graph with Roman cities and roads (customized)

A valued multigraph will represent the transportation costs associated to travel.

Cities with Populations

Cities from ORBIS with associated population estimates are in another file (https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0208744.s008)

# ancient Roman cities with population estimates
s008 <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/sdam-au/R_code/master/data/s008.txt")

Look at some entries:

lbs0 <- as.vector(s008[match(as.numeric(dimnames(net)[[1]]), s008$objectid),2])
# force directed layout with customized node labels
multigraph(net*100, directed=FALSE, layout="force", seed=1, scope=scp, lbs=lbs0)

Graph with large Roman cities and road network

In principle, the population size can be reflected in the graph of this network

# seventh column has population estimates
popl <- as.vector(s008[match(as.numeric(dimnames(net)[[1]]), s008$objectid),7])
# force directed layout with customized node size and labels
multigraph(net*100, directed=FALSE, layout="force", seed=1, scope=scp, lbs=lbs0, cex=popl)

Graph with large Roman cities and road network (customized)

Coordinates

Certainly, other layout options for the graph may apply as well including using the coordinates of the settlements. We use the coordinates found in s006 to make the new plot

# coordinates are the third and fourth columns
cds <- as.vector(s006[match(as.numeric(dimnames(net)[[1]]), s006$objectid), 3:4])

However, there are three duplicate labels in s006.

# city names are in the second column
rownames(cds) <- as.vector(s006[match(as.numeric(dimnames(net)[[1]]), s006$objectid), 2])

Network centrality

Different network centrality measures serve to assess the prominence of the entities in this system. For example, degree centrality measures a node’s importance based on the number of its neighbors, which equals to the row or column sum in the adjacency matrix representing connections.

Before computing centrality measures, however, the above Error leads us to work with a cleaned version of this dataset, which is found in:

  • Plotting Roman Roads (11-Aug-2021)
source(file="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/sdam-au/R_code/master/data/ponet.r")

Object ponet has a network component with the ties as an edgelist

We produce the adjacency matrix in net from the edgelist

netpo <- multiplex::read.srt(ponet$net, header=TRUE)

Since the links are transporytation costs, the network is valued. To compute degree centrality, dichotomize the ties with the minimum weight as cut-off value.

netdpo <- multiplex::dichot(netpo, c=min(netpo[netpo > 0]))
# degree centraliy
netpodc <- colSums(netdpo)
# replace id by label
names(netpodc) <- ponet$attr[match(as.numeric(names(netpodc)), ponet$attr$id),2]

The we look at the most prominent nodes in the graph

    Delos    Rhodos     Ratae  Carthago  Eburacum Londinium 
       21        20        12        11        11        11 
require("magrittr")
netpodc %>% 
  sort(decreasing=TRUE) %>% 
  head()
